You use a union type.
For example, let's say you had an interface with two methods that returned different types:
```typescript
interface A {
  method1(): string;
  method2(): number;
}
```
If your implementation of `A` knows that the return values are never going to be both a string and a number at the same time, then you could write:
```typescript
class B implements A {
  public method1() { return 'hello world'; }
  public method2() { return 5; }
}
```
Instead of having to specify the return type for each individual method as a string or a number, you can simply declare them as part of the union type. So the declaration would look like this:
```typescript
class B implements A {
  public method1(): string | number; // this is saying that either method1 returns a string, or it returns a number (or both)
  public method2(): number;         // this says method2 always returns a number
}
```

Now, when we instantiate our class B, we don't need to explicitly specify which methods are going to get called:
```typescript
const b = new B(); // because the return type of method1 is declared as being a string or a number, the compiler automatically infers that the method will always return a string if no other method gets called
b.method1();       // this call is okay because the return type of method1 is a string
b.method2();       // this call is also okay because the return type of method2 is a number
b.method3();       // since method3 doesn't exist, we get a compilation error!
```

